Step 2 — nvcc PTX-diff perf oracle (step 1 vs CUDA C wmma::fragment ref):
  Source CUDA C:
    __global__ void wmma_16x16_ref(const __half *a, const __half *b, float *c) {
        fragment<matrix_a, 16, 16, 16, __half, row_major> A;
        fragment<matrix_b, 16, 16, 16, __half, col_major> B;
        fragment<accumulator, 16, 16, 16, float> C;
        fill_fragment(C, 0.0f);
        load_matrix_sync(A, a, 16);
        load_matrix_sync(B, b, 16);
        mma_sync(C, A, B, C);
        store_matrix_sync(c, C, 16, mem_row_major);
    }

  Build: nvcc -arch=sm_80 -ptx /tmp/wmma_ref.cu

  Comparison:
    hexa step1 PTX  : 9 opcode-histogram entries, 13 total instr
    nvcc wmma_ref   : 5 opcode-histogram entries, 7 total instr
    hexa step1 SASS : 40 instr
    nvcc wmma_ref   : 87 SASS instr
    delta_sass      : -47 (hexa 53.9% of nvcc reference)

  Observation:
    nvcc emits fill_fragment(C, 0.0f) initialization SASS (~47 instr)
    that hexa-emit skips. The 4 redundant non-.global wmma stubs in
    hexa PTX get optimized away by ptxas at SASS lowering.

  Cleanup opportunity (cosmetic):
    Future codegen cycle could elide the redundant non-.global
    wmma.{load,store,mma} variants from the PTX emit pass. No perf
    impact (SASS is byte-eq pre/post this cleanup), but PTX text
    becomes shorter and easier to inspect via hexa gpu disasm.

